2. Livy was not in our modern sense a historian. He was a rhetorician, who, with honesty, patriotism, and moral fervor, devoted himself to setting forth the received account of Roman history in a manner that should be interesting, instructive, and elevating. Of law, politiCS, religion, and tactics he had no special knowledge, even as they were in his own day, much less as they were in the early times of which he writeS. Of the

events narrated in his earlier bookS, especially in the two in this volume, historic truth was then and still is unattainable.
